				 Jatropha project on the cards
 KAKOLY CHATTERJEE																								Dimapur, Nov. 6: D1 Williamson Magor Bio Fuel Ltd is planning to invest Rs 1,500 crore to plant and process jatropha seeds in the eastern and northeastern regions of the country.																								Kaushik Saikia, chief project manager of D1 Williamson Magor  an equal joint venture between the UK-based bio-fuel producer D1 and Indian tea company Williamson Magor  said the area under jatropha would be increased to 1.25 lakh hectares by the end of next year.																								Around 40,000 farmers are involved in jatropha cultivation in the region. D1 Williamson has invested around Rs 12 crore in procuring seeds, distributing saplings and training farmers to grow this biofuel crop, Saikia said.																								The company will increase its investment depending on the success of the project.																								Jatropha curcas is a tall bush that can grow in semi-arid conditions. 
